I"«<p>Varnish is an excellent-looking ‚ÄúHTTP accelerator‚Äù, designed specifically as a high-performance caching reverse-proxy to sit in front of your hard-working application servers, and relieve them of load.  It‚Äôs a bit of a pain in the ass to install from source on JeOS, though.  Here‚Äôs what I ended up doing:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Install XSLTProc:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo apt-get install xsltproc
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Install some helpful GNU tools:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo apt-get install automake autoconf libtool libncurses5
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Install <code class="highlighter-rouge">groff-base</code>.  If you don‚Äôt do this, your compilation will fail because <a href="http://www.linuxcommand.org/man_pages/soelim1.html"><code class="highlighter-rouge">soelim</code></a> isn‚Äôt available:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo apt-get install groff-base
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Install Subversion:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo apt-get install subversion
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Checkout the Varnish trunk:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>mkdir -p ~/src
cd ~/src
svn co http://varnish.projects.linpro.no/svn/trunk/varnish-cache
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Generate <code class="highlighter-rouge">configure</code> and makefiles:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>cd ~/src/varnish-cache
./autogen.sh
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Configure, make, test (this is SVN trunk, after all), install.  This step (particularly the tests) will take a while, go make some tea:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>./configure &amp;&amp; make &amp;&amp; make check &amp;&amp; sudo make install
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Tell JeOS where to look for Varnish‚Äôs shared libraries.  I can‚Äôt imagine why the installer doesn‚Äôt do this, I‚Äôll assume for the moment that it‚Äôs an artifact of building directly from SVN.  If you don‚Äôt do this, you‚Äôll get errors like ‚Äúvarnishd: error while loading shared libraries: libvarnish.so.1: cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory‚Äù:</p>

    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo ldconfig -n /usr/local/lib
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Go read the <a href="http://varnish.projects.linpro.no/wiki/Introduction">Varnish introduction</a>.  That‚Äôs what I‚Äôm doing at the moment‚Ä¶ it seems like a good next step.  :)</p>
  </li>
</ol>

